<main class="main">
  <div class="page-header">
    <h1 class="page-title">Numerical Methods</h1>
    <p class="lead">
      Because a closed-form analytical solution is intractable for the full coupled system,
      we deploy numerical integration techniques. We implemented three approaches to compare accuracy and stability.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="grid-2" style="margin-bottom:20px;">

    <div class="card">
      <div class="card-header">
        <div class="card-title">Euler Method (Forward)</div>
      </div>
      <div class="card-body">
        <p style="font-size:13px;color:#6b7280;margin-bottom:14px;line-height:1.6;">
          A first-order method. Simple to implement, but highly susceptible to instability
          for stiff equations unless the step size <code>h</code> is exceedingly small.
        </p>
        <div class="code-block">function [T, Y] = forward_euler(ode_fun, t_span, y0, h)
    t = t_span(1):h:t_span(2);
    n = length(t);
    y = zeros(length(y0), n);
    y(:,1) = y0;

    for i = 1:(n-1)
        y(:,i+1) = y(:,i) + h * ode_fun(t(i), y(:,i));
    end

    T = t';
    Y = y';
end</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <div class="card-header">
        <div class="card-title">Runge-Kutta 4th Order (RK4)</div>
      </div>
      <div class="card-body">
        <p style="font-size:13px;color:#6b7280;margin-bottom:14px;line-height:1.6;">
          A robust 4th-order method that evaluates the derivative at four points per step.
          Offers an excellent balance of computational cost and accuracy for our system.
        </p>
        <div class="code-block">function [T, Y] = rk4(ode_fun, t_span, y0, h)
    t = t_span(1):h:t_span(2);
    n = length(t);
    y = zeros(length(y0), n);
    y(:,1) = y0;

    for i = 1:(n-1)
        k1 = ode_fun(t(i), y(:,i));
        k2 = ode_fun(t(i) + h/2, y(:,i) + h/2 * k1);
        k3 = ode_fun(t(i) + h/2, y(:,i) + h/2 * k2);
        k4 = ode_fun(t(i) + h, y(:,i) + h * k3);

        y(:,i+1) = y(:,i) + (h/6) * (k1 + 2*k2 + 2*k3 + k4);
    end

    T = t';
    Y = y';
end</div>
      </div>
    </div>

  </div>

  <div class="card" style="margin-bottom:36px;">
    <div class="card-header">
      <div class="card-title">MATLAB ode45 (Adaptive Solver)</div>
    </div>
    <div class="card-body">
      <p style="font-size:13.5px;color:#6b7280;line-height:1.7;">
        As a benchmark, we use MATLAB's built-in <code>ode45</code>, which is based on an explicit
        Runge-Kutta (4,5) formula — the Dormand-Prince pair. It uses adaptive step sizing to keep
        the local error within specified tolerances (RelTol and AbsTol). Our manual RK4 and Euler
        implementations are compared against the <code>ode45</code> output to assess error accumulation.
      </p>
    </div>
